we didn't have any bread.</i>

221
00:18:17.054 --> 00:18:19.598
And you know you don't want
to make Joan Collins mad.

222
00:18:20.182 --> 00:18:21.141
(thwacks)

223
00:18:21.225 --> 00:18:23.560
(tense music)

224
00:18:23.644 --> 00:18:26.105
WOLFGANG:
<i>So. I stretched out a pizza dough.</i>

225
00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:30.567
<i>Added some finely chopped onions.</i>

226
00:18:32.361 --> 00:18:34.488
<i>and baked it for a few minutes.</i>

227
00:18:36.115 --> 00:18:38.534
<i>And I put some dill cream on it.</i>

228
00:18:38.617 --> 00:18:41.328
<i>I put the smoked salmon.
cut really thin on it.</i>

229
00:18:42.621 --> 00:18:47.709
A few dollops of caviar.
and I said. "Wow. this is perfect."

230
00:18:50.712 --> 00:18:54.716
I think. the best food comes from somebody
that knows the rules.

231
00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:56.093
and then can break 'em.

232
00:18:57.678 --> 00:19:00.639
NANCY: <i>What's interesting
about the smoked salmon pizza was that.</i>

233
00:19:00.722 --> 00:19:03.976
<i>it had no tomato sauce
and it had no cheese.</i>

234
00:19:04.059 --> 00:19:06.103
As simple as that sounds today.

235
00:19:06.186 --> 00:19:09.690
I don't think anyone had done
a pizza like that before.

236
00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:13.986
REPORTER 2: <i>Sometimes. when you ask
Wolfgang Puck what's cooking.</i>

237
00:19:14.069 --> 00:19:17.364
<i>you may not understand the answer.
but you're bound to like it.</i>

238
00:19:18.365 --> 00:19:21.285
LAURIE: <i>When it came to food.
Wolf was always willing.</i>

239
00:19:21.368 --> 00:19:25.205
to go in a different direction
and take big risks.

240
00:19:28.417 --> 00:19:33.505
NANCY: <i>With Chinois. he wanted
to use his French techniques.</i>

241
00:19:33.589 --> 00:19:35.674
<i>to complement Chinese cooking.</i>

242
00:19:36.758 --> 00:19:38.927
That was the beginning of fusion.

243
00:19:39.887 --> 00:19:42.014
(upbeat music)

244
00:19:43.682 --> 00:19:45.684
(sizzling)

245
00:19:47.227 --> 00:19:52.900
EVAN: <i>Wolf's Chinese chicken salad
at Chinois birthed this explosion.</i>

246
00:19:52.983 --> 00:19:56.778
of the Asian chicken salad
forever and ever.

247
00:19:56.862 --> 00:20:02.659
Like you can go to like supermarket
and find Asian chicken salad in a bag.

248
00:20:02.743 --> 00:20:03.952
Like. he did that.

249
00:20:04.036 --> 00:20:06.288
MAN 2: Making chicken salad. right.
Chinese chicken salad.

250
00:20:06.371 --> 00:20:08.040
WOLFGANG: Excellent Chinese chicken salad.

251
00:20:10.417 --> 00:20:15.464
Sometimes. I think. inventions come
where you least expect it.

252
00:20:16.256 --> 00:20:18.634
WOLFGANG: <i>All of a sudden.
out of necessity.</i>

253
00:20:18.717 --> 00:20:20.219
<i>something good comes out.</i>

254
00:20:39.071 --> 00:20:43.992
<i>I got really lucky when I got the job
at the Park Hotel.</i>

255
00:20:45.118 --> 00:20:48.872
<i>I started to stamp the French fries.
peeled onions.</i>

256
00:20:48.956 --> 00:20:52.125
<i>They showed me how to make
the pancakes in the pans.</i>

257
00:20:52.793 --> 00:20:55.796
<i>Little by little I started to get better.</i>

258
00:20:57.547 --> 00:20:58.840
(in German)
RESTAURATEUR: Right. Here you go.

259
00:20:58.924 --> 00:21:00.509
And wiener schnitzel.

260
00:21:00.592 --> 00:21:02.844
-Thank you.
-Enjoy your meal.

261
00:21:03.011 --> 00:21:04.346
Thank you.

262
00:21:06.598 --> 00:21:08.058
Just a little.

263
00:21:08.141 --> 00:21:10.936
(in English)
WOLFGANG: <i>I was so proud of myself</i>

264
00:21:11.019 --> 00:21:13.939
<i>when I could heat up some peas
or some carrots</i>

265
00:21:14.022 --> 00:21:15.899
<i>or make the chicken soup.</i>

266
00:21:16.441 --> 00:21:20.362
<i>It made me feel really good
about what I was doing.</i>

267
00:21:27.786 --> 00:21:31.581
<i>About two and a half years
into the apprenticeship.</i>

268
00:21:31.665 --> 00:21:34.793
we had a French restaurant from Dijon

269
00:21:35.377 --> 00:21:38.922
come and cooked for a week in the hotel.

270
00:21:42.634 --> 00:21:45.512
<i>They did all these things I never saw.</i>

271
00:21:48.307 --> 00:21:53.270
<i>I was so inspired by French cooking
that I knew at that point.</i>

272
00:21:53.353 --> 00:21:56.982
I had to go to France
and experience it and learn it.

273
00:21:57.232 --> 00:21:59.359
(lively music)

274
00:22:01.862 --> 00:22:05.907
WOLFGANG: <i>I was 19 years old
when I started at Baumanière.</i>

275
00:22:05.991 --> 00:22:09.036
<i>a famous three-star restaurant in France.</i>

276
00:22:10.245 --> 00:22:14.416
<i>They had like five French cooks there
and I was the youngest one.</i>

277
00:22:14.499 --> 00:22:17.336
and I didn't speak French.
It was pretty rough.

278
00:22:19.629 --> 00:22:23.425
<i>We had a huge farm there
with six gardeners.</i>

279
00:22:23.925 --> 00:22:29.222
<i>They brought the finest green beans
or apricots or great melons.</i>

280
00:22:30.098 --> 00:22:33.435
<i>So. we cooked
with only the best ingredients.</i>

281
00:22:34.311 --> 00:22:38.565
The flavors felt so amazing.
I had never experienced that.

282
00:22:38.648 --> 00:22:41.276
This was a revelation for me.

283
00:22:43.695 --> 00:22:46.698
<i>Raymond Thuilier. the owner.
was a perfectionist.</i>

284
00:22:48.992 --> 00:22:52.412
<i>One day. he made a sauce
and he said. "Taste it."</i>

285
00:22:52.496 --> 00:22:57.084
I tasted it and said. "Oh. I would put
a little lemon juice and a little pepper."

286
00:22:57.167 --> 00:22:59.378
He said. "Okay. put a little lemon juice
and pepper."

287
00:23:02.172 --> 00:23:06.676
He tasted it and he says.
"Oh. good. much better."

288
00:23:09.721 --> 00:23:12.641
<i>He made me feel appreciated.</i>

289
00:23:12.724 --> 00:23:18.397
He made me feel like. "Ah. I can do that
as well as anybody in the kitchen."

290
00:23:19.856 --> 00:23:25.237
<i>After that. Raymond Thuilier
really became my mentor.</i>

291
00:23:26.363 --> 00:23:30.158
And I said. "I want to be a chef.
I want to be like him."

292
00:23:33.245 --> 00:23:35.580
(light music)

293
00:23:42.546 --> 00:23:44.548
(indistinct chatter)

294
00:23:45.966 --> 00:23:47.968
WOLFGANG: <i>After I came to France.</i>

295
00:23:48.051 --> 00:23:52.347
<i>my life started
to take steps up. up. up all the time.</i>

296
00:23:54.015 --> 00:23:56.685
<i>I was always thinking about the future.</i>

297
00:23:58.061 --> 00:23:59.813
I was still upset at my stepfather.

298
00:23:59.896 --> 00:24:02.983
and did not want to have
nothing to do with him.

299
00:24:03.608 --> 00:24:07.487
<i>So. I didn't talk to my family
for a year and a half.</i>

300
00:24:08.905 --> 00:24:10.782
I never wrote a letter nor nothing.

301
00:24:12.492 --> 00:24:16.913
<i>I wanted to stay as far away
from home as possible.</i>

302
00:24:19.458 --> 00:24:21.460
(tranquil music)

303
00:24:28.091 --> 00:24:29.593
CHRISTINA:

304
00:24:38.101 --> 00:24:42.522
(in German)

305
00:24:53.575 --> 00:24:55.202
(sobs)

306
00:25:02.751 --> 00:25:05.420
(in English)
WOLFGANG: <i>One day. at Baumanière.</i>

307
00:25:05.504 --> 00:25:09.758
<i>the dishwasher says.
"You know. I listen to the radio.</i>

308
00:25:09.841 --> 00:25:13.845
<i>and the Austrian embassy
in Paris is looking for you.</i>

309
00:25:15.388 --> 00:25:18.475
Nobody has any news.
nobody knows where you are.

310
00:25:19.267 --> 00:25:20.685
And they think you're dead."

311
00:25:21.269 --> 00:25:24.814
And so I wrote my mother a note
and said. "You know I'm in Provence.

312
00:25:24.898 --> 00:25:27.984
I like it here and everything is fine.
Don't worry."

313
00:25:30.111 --> 00:25:35.033
<i>I felt bad leaving my family but I said.</i>

314
00:25:35.700 --> 00:25:39.996
"I don't care what happened.
I will never come back home."

315
00:25:44.626 --> 00:25:47.045
(lively music)

316
00:25:50.215 --> 00:25:53.385
Every kid dreams about coming to America.

317
00:25:54.261 --> 00:25:57.597
WOLFGANG: <i>In America. everybody is rich.
Everybody drives a Cadillac.</i>

318
00:25:58.557 --> 00:26:02.602
<i>So. when I was 24. I came to California.</i>

319
00:26:04.145 --> 00:26:05.564
<i>I had very little money.</i>

320
00:26:06.314 --> 00:26:10.026
<i>So. I found an apartment
in a retirement home on Bunker Hill.</i>

321
00:26:10.110 --> 00:26:11.236
<i>with my friend Guy.</i>

322
00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:14.781
<i>cockroaches on the staircases
and everything.</i>

323
00:26:14.864 --> 00:26:16.616
but what do you want for 80 bucks?

324
00:26:17.867 --> 00:26:23.373
<i>I got a job working in a restaurant.
And I was the night chef there.</i>

325
00:26:23.456 --> 00:26:26.501
<i>But it was like
the opposite of Baumanière.</i>

326
00:26:27.252 --> 00:26:32.215
<i>Things had to be flown in frozen.
no fresh ingredients.</i>

327
00:26:32.549 --> 00:26:36.553
<i>I got so many steaks back. and they said.
"No. it's not well done enough."</i>

328
00:26:36.636 --> 00:26:40.640
And I said.
"Oh. no. this is nothing I imagine.

329
00:26:40.724 --> 00:26:41.975
This is terrible."

330
00:26:42.392 --> 00:26:47.522
HENRY: <i>This is Henry the magician.
And here's your frozen food magic.</i>

331
00:26:47.606 --> 00:26:50.233
ANNOUNCER 1:
<i>Children often need between-meal snacks.</i>

332
00:26:50.317 --> 00:26:51.985
<i>snacks like Hostess Twinkies.</i>

333
00:26:52.068 --> 00:26:54.279
<i>They help your child go and grow.</i>

334
00:26:54.362 --> 00:26:55.405
ANNOUNCER 2: <i>Stop!</i>

335
00:26:55.488 --> 00:26:58.033
<i>You don't have to peel onions
or mess with garlic.</i>

336
00:26:58.116 --> 00:27:00.535
<i>Taste Tap push-button foods are here.</i>

337
00:27:00.619 --> 00:27:05.498
It's hard to remember today
what food was like in America in the '70s.

338
00:27:07.250 --> 00:27:09.085
RUTH: <i>We were very ashamed.</i>

339
00:27:10.295 --> 00:27:13.214
<i>We thought of American food
as hamburgers. hot dogs.</i>

340
00:27:13.298 --> 00:27:15.383
<i>we don't have anything good here.</i>

341
00:27:17.802 --> 00:27:20.764
<i>People were used to tasteless tomatoes.</i>

342
00:27:20.847 --> 00:27:24.476
<i>and produce that had
no flavor and no aroma.</i>

343
00:27:26.645 --> 00:27:28.897
French chefs would come over and say.

344
00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:31.483
"Oh. my god.
I have to import everything from France."

345
00:27:33.610 --> 00:27:38.531
In those days. restaurants
were just about sauce and meat.

346
00:27:38.615 --> 00:27:41.159
<i>maybe a flaming dessert or something.</i>

347
00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:43.828
<i>Food had gotten into a big rut.</i>

348
00:27:50.377 --> 00:27:55.090
WOLFGANG: <i>After two months or so
of working in the restaurants downtown.</i>

349
00:27:55.173 --> 00:27:58.426
<i>I walked one day to get an espresso.</i>

350
00:27:59.094 --> 00:28:02.097
<i>And all of a sudden.
I see my friend from Paris.</i>

351
00:28:02.180 --> 00:28:04.432
<i>and I said.
"What the hell are you doing here?"</i>

352
00:28:04.516 --> 00:28:08.395
And he said. "Well. I'm working
in a restaurant called Ma Maison."

353
00:28:10.063 --> 00:28:13.983
<i>The owner is the nephew
of the owner of La Tour d'Argent.</i>

354
00:28:14.526 --> 00:28:16.945
<i>three-star restaurant from Paris.</i>

355
00:28:17.028 --> 00:28:19.239
So. I said.
"Wow. that must be an amazing restaurant."

356
00:28:19.322 --> 00:28:21.491
Maybe you can help me find a job.

357
00:28:23.952 --> 00:28:26.788
<i>He got me a job as a cook at Ma Maison.</i>

358
00:28:26.871 --> 00:28:28.206
I was so excited.

359
00:28:28.915 --> 00:28:31.793
<i>But the first day I walked in.</i>

360
00:28:31.876 --> 00:28:37.215
<i>and I see Astroturf on the floor
and plastic chairs and everything.</i>

361
00:28:37.298 --> 00:28:41.761
Not even a walk-in refrigerator.
They had refrigerators lined up outside.

362
00:28:41.845 --> 00:28:46.391
I said. "Oh. my god. this is the nephew
of the owner from La Tour d'Argent."

363
00:28:46.474 --> 00:28:48.476
(upbeat music)

364
00:28:49.227 --> 00:28:51.396
<i>Patrick was very arrogant.</i>

365
00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:57.360
He had always a nice suit on
with the little carnation here.

366
00:28:57.444 --> 00:29:01.698
and talked like he had the best restaurant
in Los Angeles.

367
00:29:01.823 --> 00:29:03.491
<i>but it was nothing.</i>

368
00:29:04.617 --> 00:29:07.537
RUTH: <i>Circa. 1979. 1980.</i>

369
00:29:08.037 --> 00:29:11.583
<i>the restaurateur thought he was the guy.</i>

370
00:29:11.666 --> 00:29:14.961
And the chef was the blue-collar guy

371
00:29:15.044 --> 00:29:17.881
toiling away in the kitchen. expendable.

372
00:29:29.893 --> 00:29:31.895
PATRICK:

373
00:29:40.403 --> 00:29:42.322
WOLFGANG: <i>So. I start working there.</i>

374
00:29:42.947 --> 00:29:46.576
And two weeks later.
I saw the worst review.

375
00:29:49.704 --> 00:29:52.123
<i>So. Patrick fired the chef there.</i>

376
00:29:52.207 --> 00:29:55.710
And he said. "Wolfgang. take over
the restaurant and be the chef here."

377
00:29:56.628 --> 00:29:58.338
<i>I couldn't believe it.</i>

378
00:29:59.130 --> 00:30:02.175
But Ma Maison had a really bad reputation.

379
00:30:02.258 --> 00:30:05.011
And boy. when I looked
in that refrigerator.

380
00:30:05.303 --> 00:30:09.599
<i>the only food available was a frozen meat.</i>

381
00:30:10.475 --> 00:30:12.727
And I said.
"Hell. no. I cannot cook like that."

382
00:30:22.445 --> 00:30:24.864
(sizzles)

383
00:30:31.246 --> 00:30:34.541
WOLFGANG: <i>After I got the job.
people laughed about it.</i>

384
00:30:34.624 --> 00:30:36.501
<i>because there was nobody
going to Ma Maison.</i>

385
00:30:37.377 --> 00:30:41.673
<i>Everybody said. "Oh. my god. you made
a mistake to go to this restaurant."</i>

386
00:30:43.758 --> 00:30:47.470
<i>A lot of people think the grass
is always greener somewhere else.</i>

387
00:30:48.346 --> 00:30:52.976
<i>They say. "Well. I have a problem here.
let's throw in the towel and quit."</i>

388
00:30:54.727 --> 00:30:59.440
But I believe the grass is greener
where you water it the most.

389
00:31:01.276 --> 00:31:06.322
<i>If you put in the effort and put in
the work. no it only can get better.</i>

390
00:31:11.035 --> 00:31:15.164
<i>When I started at Ma Maison.
the food was terrible.</i>

391
00:31:15.248 --> 00:31:18.418
<i>So. I said. "How we gonna fix that?"</i>

392
00:31:19.419 --> 00:31:23.381
You start with the best product
and then you don't screw it up.

393
00:31:24.716 --> 00:31:27.594
TOM: <i>In a wide-open space.
20 miles north of San Diego</i>

394
00:31:27.677 --> 00:31:30.013
<i>sits a modest roadside stand.</i>

395
00:31:30.096 --> 00:31:34.642
<i>By contrast. fancy cars line up
at the shack six days a week.</i>

396
00:31:34.726 --> 00:31:37.020
<i>They come to buy Tom Chino's produce.</i>

397
00:31:37.103 --> 00:31:40.481
<i>the most carefully grown fruits
and vegetables anywhere.</i>

398
00:31:41.107 --> 00:31:45.445
WOLFGANG: <i>When I went the first time
to the Chino Farm in Rancho Santa Fe.</i>

399
00:31:45.528 --> 00:31:48.907
<i>and I saw all the vegetables there.</i>

400
00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:51.743
<i>my eyes lit up and I said.</i>

401
00:31:51.826 --> 00:31:56.247
"Oh. my god.
this is as good as Baumanière.

402
00:31:56.331 --> 00:31:57.582
I can really cook."

403
00:31:57.665 --> 00:32:00.168
(lively music)

404
00:32:02.128 --> 00:32:07.008
RUTH: <i>Wolf was the first person in L.A.
to find the Chino Ranch.</i>

405
00:32:07.717 --> 00:32:11.137
<i>He started using their fantastic produce.</i>

406
00:32:12.639 --> 00:32:17.477
Suddenly. he's serving this very
simple food that's incredibly flavorful.

407
00:32:18.561 --> 00:32:22.982
Making these salads that people would go
"Oh. my god. this is a tomato?"

408
00:32:24.567 --> 00:32:26.486
<i>And that was really new.</i>

409
00:32:31.532 --> 00:32:35.828
The quality of the ingredients became
so much a part of the food at Ma Maison.

410
00:32:35.912 --> 00:32:37.372
Where's our tuna?

411
00:32:37.872 --> 00:32:40.375
NANCY: <i>He made a daily trip
to the fish market.</i>

412
00:32:40.458 --> 00:32:45.755
He made a weekly two-hour-plus trip
to pick up vegetables.

413
00:32:46.297 --> 00:32:48.299
That was very. very unique.

414
00:32:50.009 --> 00:32:55.098
LAURIE: <i>He showed us how to make
American food in a whole new way.</i>

415
00:32:55.848 --> 00:33:00.812
Bringing it all together and making it
feel like this is California on a plate.

416
00:33:00.895 --> 00:33:04.732
It's fantastic. you’re gonna love it.
and bon appétit.

417
00:33:04.816 --> 00:33:05.817
(laughs)

418
00:33:07.402 --> 00:33:10.613
WOLFGANG: <i>It was hard the first six months
but I worked hard.</i>

419
00:33:10.697 --> 00:33:14.701
And little by little. the restaurant
started to get better.

420
00:33:14.784 --> 00:33:16.536
and I was so proud of it.

421
00:33:18.246 --> 00:33:22.917
To get a table in the restaurant
was pretty much almost impossible.

422
00:33:24.377 --> 00:33:27.964
MICHAEL: <i>Wolf was in the kitchen.
never to be seen.</i>

423
00:33:28.047 --> 00:33:31.467
<i>making food like none of us
had ever eaten before.</i>

424
00:33:33.219 --> 00:33:38.433
<i>But the restaurant really revolved
around Patrick Terrail.</i>

425
00:33:45.106 --> 00:33:47.275
ROBIN:
<i>Hollywood's Ma Maison has terrific food</i>

