00:34:12.175 --> 00:34:15.386
<i>buy fresh ingredients
and then drive to Ma Maison</i>

436
00:34:15.470 --> 00:34:19.640
where I worked from five in the afternoon
until two or three in the morning.

437
00:34:19.724 --> 00:34:23.061
We knew clubs who started to open up
at two in the morning.

438
00:34:23.144 --> 00:34:26.981
and we used to hang out
until the day came up every day.

439
00:34:27.065 --> 00:34:29.692
(upbeat music)

440
00:34:31.027 --> 00:34:33.738
WOLFGANG:
<i>One night. I went to dance with a girl.</i>

441
00:34:34.405 --> 00:34:36.491
<i>We talked and she said. "What do you do?"</i>

442
00:34:36.574 --> 00:34:40.620
And I said. "I'm a cook. I'm a chef."
And she looked at me. "A cook?"

443
00:34:42.997 --> 00:34:44.332
The song was over.

444
00:34:44.415 --> 00:34:47.376
she left me on the dance floor
and walked away from me.

445
00:34:47.460 --> 00:34:49.045
I was like. "What? What did I do?"

446
00:34:49.128 --> 00:34:51.798
I didn't even walk on her toes
or anything.

447
00:34:51.881 --> 00:34:54.133
So from then on. when I went to a club.

448
00:34:54.217 --> 00:34:56.385
I always said I'm a racecar driver
in Europe.

449
00:34:57.261 --> 00:34:59.722
Okay. we're going to add our milk
to our egg yolks and...

450
00:34:59.806 --> 00:35:03.935
WOLFGANG: <i>At that time. I was teaching
cooking classes at Ma Maison.</i>

451
00:35:04.018 --> 00:35:07.980
And one day. I looked up
while I was making my butter sauce.

452
00:35:08.064 --> 00:35:10.316
and there in the back was Barbara.
She's snacking.

453
00:35:11.776 --> 00:35:14.070
BARBARA: <i>I walked into the class
and sat down.</i>

454
00:35:14.821 --> 00:35:18.157
Wolf looked up for a moment
and he spotted me.

455
00:35:18.241 --> 00:35:22.620
and he had a big.
like a big wad of butter in his hands

456
00:35:22.703 --> 00:35:26.707
and he proceeded
to just drop it on the floor.

457
00:35:27.458 --> 00:35:32.171
And things progressed
rather quickly after that.

458
00:35:32.255 --> 00:35:34.340
(tranquil music)

459
00:35:37.718 --> 00:35:39.512
WOLFGANG: <i>Barbara was the beautiful woman.</i>

460
00:35:40.638 --> 00:35:43.850
<i>She was very outgoing
and she was very smart and talented.</i>

461
00:35:47.436 --> 00:35:51.607
BARBARA: <i>He was very sweet and
he was very focused on what he was doing.</i>

462
00:35:52.650 --> 00:35:55.945
<i>He was a little unattainable
in certain ways. too.</i>

463
00:35:56.696 --> 00:36:00.783
The standard joke was. if I would dress up
as a baby carrot.

464
00:36:01.492 --> 00:36:04.328
little baby carrot.
I'd probably get more attention.

465
00:36:04.912 --> 00:36:06.914
But I like a challenge.

466
00:36:10.168 --> 00:36:14.839
RUTH: <i>Barbara was really the one
pushing Wolf forward.</i>

467
00:36:16.257 --> 00:36:20.052
<i>He was the genius and the chef.</i>

468
00:36:21.220 --> 00:36:26.350
But she was the one who saw it
and said. "Don't undersell yourself.

469
00:36:26.893 --> 00:36:28.060
<i>You're really great."</i>

470
00:36:33.316 --> 00:36:34.734
(sizzles)

471
00:36:34.817 --> 00:36:37.361
Voilà. you see it starts
to get nice and brown.

472
00:36:37.695 --> 00:36:39.697
Now. should you always put
the skin down first?

473
00:36:39.780 --> 00:36:42.408
-Does it make a difference?
-Yeah. always the skin first.

474
00:36:44.118 --> 00:36:48.164
Wolfgang was always telling me
about his dreams and desires.

475
00:36:48.247 --> 00:36:50.333
about work and wishes and he said.

476
00:36:50.416 --> 00:36:53.127
"You know. one day I would really like
to have my own restaurant."

477
00:36:53.628 --> 00:36:56.255
And I said. "Yeah. really. you should."

478
00:36:56.339 --> 00:36:58.341
Okay. we're gonna sauté
all our vegetables now.

479
00:36:58.424 --> 00:37:00.760
First. the bacon so the fat goes out.

480
00:37:00.843 --> 00:37:03.262
BARBARA: <i>One day. I found this check.</i>

481
00:37:03.346 --> 00:37:06.599
I said. "Wolf. is this your paycheck?"
He said. "Yeah."

482
00:37:06.682 --> 00:37:12.063
I said. "Is this all you make a week
for working as hard as you do?

483
00:37:12.146 --> 00:37:17.401
You should go in and ask Patrick
to double the salary."

484
00:37:17.485 --> 00:37:19.487
(dramatic music)

485
00:37:20.154 --> 00:37:25.284
WOLFGANG: <i>After I had been working there
for six years. I went to see Patrick.</i>

486
00:37:25.368 --> 00:37:28.746
And Patrick said. "You know. maybe I make
you a partner in the restaurant."

487
00:37:29.789 --> 00:37:33.334
I said. "Good."
"But I gonna pay you a little bit less."

488
00:37:35.920 --> 00:37:39.882
<i>Before I came to Ma Maison.
Ma Maison was almost bankrupt.</i>

489
00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:43.636
<i>And as soon as I started.
we started to go uphill.</i>

490
00:37:44.971 --> 00:37:47.765
<i>But Patrick took all the credit for it.</i>

491
00:37:49.809 --> 00:37:52.937
<i>And he made me feel</i>

492
00:37:53.020 --> 00:37:56.232
like I'm not that important
to the restaurant.

493
00:37:59.193 --> 00:38:01.529
PATRICK:

494
00:38:04.699 --> 00:38:08.244
Ma Maison was really my house.

495
00:38:08.869 --> 00:38:11.956
You know. I build it from nothing.

496
00:38:14.625 --> 00:38:18.671
I went to Patrick and I told him
I want to be an equal partner.

497
00:38:18.754 --> 00:38:20.464
It has to be fifty-fifty.

498
00:38:31.434 --> 00:38:36.814
He pointed at me and said.
"You know. I always gonna own 51 percent."

499
00:38:37.857 --> 00:38:40.276
I pointed back on him and said. "Me too."

500
00:38:41.861 --> 00:38:44.113
WOLFGANG: <i>So that was that.</i>

501
00:38:44.196 --> 00:38:46.365
<i>Then I said. "Now I have to leave."</i>

502
00:39:01.714 --> 00:39:05.301
<i>I always wanted to open my own restaurant.</i>

503
00:39:06.594 --> 00:39:08.054
<i>It was my dream.</i>

504
00:39:10.473 --> 00:39:13.934
<i>But Ma Maison was the restaurant in L.A.</i>

505
00:39:14.643 --> 00:39:18.689
<i>To leave at the pinnacle. it's crazy.</i>

506
00:39:19.273 --> 00:39:21.484
(somber music)

507
00:39:26.030 --> 00:39:31.202
<i>Patrick told the newspapers that
I have no idea how to run a restaurant.</i>

508
00:39:31.285 --> 00:39:33.621
<i>I'm only a cook and said.</i>

509
00:39:33.704 --> 00:39:39.377
"Wolfgang will come back in three months
begging for a job."

510
00:39:41.670 --> 00:39:44.965
WOLFGANG:
<i>I said. "My God. this is. like. déjà vu."</i>

511
00:39:46.550 --> 00:39:50.805
<i>All these crazy words reminded me
of my stepfather.</i>

512
00:39:51.639 --> 00:39:54.350
<i>It made me feel like I'm gonna fail.</i>

513
00:39:56.185 --> 00:40:00.231
BARBARA: <i>Wolf was very talented
and passionate and focused.</i>

514
00:40:01.023 --> 00:40:03.818
but I don't think
he thought enough of himself.

515
00:40:04.318 --> 00:40:08.447
He was constantly having nightmares about
what if this fails. what if this fails.

516
00:40:09.782 --> 00:40:12.576
<i>I was constantly telling him.
"You can do it.</i>

517
00:40:13.452 --> 00:40:14.578
<i>We can do this."</i>

518
00:40:15.579 --> 00:40:17.581
(tranquil music)

519
00:40:24.964 --> 00:40:27.258
WOLFGANG:
<i>The whole time. I was so nervous.</i>

520
00:40:28.050 --> 00:40:30.261
<i>Barbara was very supportive of it.</i>

521
00:40:32.221 --> 00:40:35.724
She had also confidence in me
that I can make it work.

522
00:40:38.436 --> 00:40:43.065
<i>I think. Barbara helped me remember
that I don't quit.</i>

523
00:40:43.732 --> 00:40:45.693
I don't give up easily.

524
00:40:49.697 --> 00:40:54.869
He had no idea if he was gonna be able
to actually run a business.

525
00:40:54.952 --> 00:40:57.079
I mean. this was all new to him.

526
00:40:59.165 --> 00:41:01.417
RUTH: <i>But I think it was this moment.
you know.</i>

527
00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:04.795
<i>either you jump off the diving board.</i>

528
00:41:04.879 --> 00:41:09.300
<i>or you resign yourself
to standing in the back of the kitchen</i>

529
00:41:09.383 --> 00:41:11.427
with your white toque on
for the rest of your life.

530
00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:13.095
and he took the plunge.

531
00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:35.743
BARBARA: <i>Wolfgang found
this restaurant space in Hollywood.</i>

532
00:41:36.327 --> 00:41:39.914
It was a dive. Such disrepair.

533
00:41:39.997 --> 00:41:42.291
<i>We had to get a blaster in there</i>

534
00:41:42.374 --> 00:41:46.378
to get three-inches thick grease
off the walls

535
00:41:46.462 --> 00:41:48.130
that had been there for 30 years.

536
00:41:48.923 --> 00:41:52.301
<i>I remember I was upside down
scrubbing the gum off the bottom.</i>

537
00:41:52.384 --> 00:41:54.512
<i>of all the old tables for days.</i>

538
00:41:55.095 --> 00:41:59.183
<i>We didn't have a lot of money at the time.
so we had to do what we could.</i>

539
00:42:05.105 --> 00:42:08.400
RUTH:
<i>Wolf's initial idea of opening Spago.</i>

540
00:42:08.484 --> 00:42:10.945
was that it was going to be
this little pizza place.

541
00:42:11.028 --> 00:42:14.573
like one he had gone to
in Saint-Rémy in Provence.

542
00:42:14.657 --> 00:42:16.242
checked tablecloths.

543
00:42:16.325 --> 00:42:19.537
And Barbara was the one who said. "No...

544
00:42:20.287 --> 00:42:22.706
Let's do something more ambitious."

545
00:42:28.629 --> 00:42:32.883
BARBARA: <i>I didn't have a lot of design
experience but I had done theater sets.</i>

546
00:42:32.967 --> 00:42:35.469
and I thought cooking is a show.

547
00:42:35.553 --> 00:42:39.139
It was theater and he was the star.

548
00:42:39.807 --> 00:42:44.562
<i>So. I called up 911. I said. "Could I have
the number for the fire department?"</i>

549
00:42:44.645 --> 00:42:49.233
And all I said was. "Hello. sir.
we're thinking of doing a restaurant.

550
00:42:49.650 --> 00:42:55.030
that is going to have a wood-burning pizza
oven on the kitchen line.

551
00:42:55.114 --> 00:42:58.617
open in the restaurant. is that okay?"

552
00:42:58.701 --> 00:43:01.203
And he says. "Sounds okay to me. lady."

553
00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:04.039
And I hung up the phone. I turned to Wolf.

554
00:43:04.123 --> 00:43:05.791
and I said we can do this.

555
00:43:05.874 --> 00:43:08.085
(lively music)

556
00:43:10.713 --> 00:43:15.593
The day of opening. the nails
were still being pounded into the boards.

557
00:43:15.676 --> 00:43:17.970
I don't even think the menu was done then.

558
00:43:21.807 --> 00:43:27.187
The day we opened.
we had just gotten our final approvals.

559
00:43:27.271 --> 00:43:30.566
so I was able to turn on the stoves.
get stocks going.

560
00:43:30.649 --> 00:43:33.944
MARK: <i>I'd been going for. like.
about 40 hours without sleep.</i>

561
00:43:35.195 --> 00:43:39.074
They did not have electricity
until four o'clock in the afternoon.

562
00:43:41.160 --> 00:43:43.037
BARBARA: <i>We were about to open that night.</i>

563
00:43:43.120 --> 00:43:47.416
<i>and I'm still standing barefoot
on top of the exhibition counter.</i>

564
00:43:47.499 --> 00:43:49.460
getting everything adjusted correctly.

565
00:43:49.543 --> 00:43:52.588
food's still coming through the door.
everybody's trying to get dressed.

566
00:43:53.047 --> 00:43:56.342
<i>And then the doors opened. and...</i>

567
00:43:58.385 --> 00:44:00.179
organized pandemonium.

568
00:44:00.512 --> 00:44:02.514
(lively music)

569
00:44:08.520 --> 00:44:11.023
WOLFGANG: <i>To my surprise.
from the first day.</i>

570
00:44:11.106 --> 00:44:13.025
<i>it became an instant success.</i>

571
00:44:13.108 --> 00:44:14.943
It was an amazing feeling.

572
00:44:16.070 --> 00:44:20.366
We had so many customers.
so we were in the weeds every night.

573
00:44:25.162 --> 00:44:26.789
RUTH: <i>We have an 8:30 reservation.</i>

574
00:44:26.872 --> 00:44:29.124
and if you were lucky.
maybe you'd get seated at 10.

575
00:44:30.167 --> 00:44:33.879
I mean. you walked in there
and the energy just came up.

576
00:44:38.133 --> 00:44:41.762
We worked in the kitchen right up front.
there was a lot of noise.

577
00:44:41.845 --> 00:44:43.847
there was a lot of heat and flame.

578
00:44:44.890 --> 00:44:48.811
We were making pizzas
as fast as we possibly could.

579
00:44:49.645 --> 00:44:52.648
BARBARA: <i>You could smell the food
wafting across the room.</i>

580
00:44:52.773 --> 00:44:55.734
You saw the excitement.
You saw the food coming in and going out.

581
00:45:00.406 --> 00:45:03.617
WOLFGANG: <i>Everybody was asking
about the food. what it was.</i>

582
00:45:03.701 --> 00:45:07.955
So. I went out and bought some pastel
and designed my own menu.

583
00:45:08.038 --> 00:45:10.833
<i>And put on it Spago California Cuisine.</i>

584
00:45:11.500 --> 00:45:13.043
<i>People loved it.</i>

585
00:45:17.506 --> 00:45:20.884
MICHAEL: <i>He was making the best pizza.
the best salad.</i>

586
00:45:20.968 --> 00:45:24.555
<i>the best-grilled foods
you could eat. all very healthy.</i>

587
00:45:25.681 --> 00:45:28.434
<i>A lot of people
called it "California cuisine."</i>

588
00:45:28.517 --> 00:45:30.185
I just called it "Wolfgang's kitchen."

589
00:45:30.269 --> 00:45:32.271
(upbeat music)

590
00:45:36.066 --> 00:45:40.571
Wolfgang was just such a huge personality
and mostly because of that open kitchen.

591
00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:43.115
JANNIS: <i>There was no other restaurant
like that.</i>

592
00:45:44.616 --> 00:45:48.162
Every night. we said the same thing.
"Curtain up."

593
00:45:48.245 --> 00:45:50.581
And I thought to myself.
"Yeah. this is Spago."

594
00:45:54.001 --> 00:45:57.421
A year after we opened.
the <i>New York Times</i> wrote a piece.

595
00:45:57.796 --> 00:46:00.007
<i>"The Spagoization of Manhattan."</i>

596
00:46:01.258 --> 00:46:02.968
BARBARA: <i>To realize that in one year.</i>

597
00:46:03.051 --> 00:46:06.346
that restaurant had affected
the way people dine.

598
00:46:06.930 --> 00:46:11.310
<i>What casual environment putting the chefs
on stage with open kitchens?</i>

599
00:46:11.393 --> 00:46:15.105
All of that. that was monumental.

600
00:46:20.652 --> 00:46:22.654
(quirky music)

601
00:46:26.825 --> 00:46:32.164
We're roasting this chicken today
on the <i>French Chef</i>.

602
00:46:32.539 --> 00:46:35.042
JULIA: You know.
we speak of a covey of quail

603
00:46:35.125 --> 00:46:38.045
and a gaggle of geese
and a pride of lions.

604
00:46:38.462 --> 00:46:41.256
Well. this is known as a peep of chickens.

605
00:46:41.340 --> 00:46:43.008
MICHAEL: <i>At that time in the '80s.</i>

606
00:46:43.091 --> 00:46:47.638
<i>Julia Child was the only big chef
who was on television.</i>

607
00:46:48.764 --> 00:46:50.098
You had a number of cooking shows.

608
00:46:50.182 --> 00:46:52.726
particularly on local stations
all over the country.

609
00:46:52.810 --> 00:46:54.853
But no one had really gone national.

610
00:46:57.481 --> 00:46:58.565
Carrots.

611
00:47:00.776 --> 00:47:02.110
Mushrooms.

612
00:47:03.153 --> 00:47:08.283
And these snails were brought
into America from France as a food item.

613
00:47:09.827 --> 00:47:13.705
Tofu. it doesn't have much personality
in its raw form.

614
00:47:13.789 --> 00:47:16.250
CHEF 2:
It's simply begging to be flavored.

615
00:47:16.917 --> 00:47:20.921
Wolfgang was recognized
very quickly as an innovator.

616
00:47:21.004 --> 00:47:22.464
You can't smell it on the camera.

617
00:47:24.216 --> 00:47:25.217
MICHAEL: <i>We were friends.</i>

618
00:47:25.300 --> 00:47:29.263
And I went in and one day I just said
to him. "We think you should be on TV."

619
00:47:29.346 --> 00:47:31.723
(indistinct chatter)

620
00:47:31.807 --> 00:47:34.893
MICHAEL: <i>I decided that the best way
to get him on television.</i>

621
00:47:34.977 --> 00:47:37.771
was to take the president
of ABC to dinner.

622
00:47:40.566 --> 00:47:43.986
<i>And I called Wolf up and he said.
"What would you like me to do?"</i>

623
00:47:44.570 --> 00:47:49.449
We proceeded to have one of the all-time
great-tasting menus in history.

624
00:47:49.533 --> 00:47:51.577
(light music)

625
00:47:53.620 --> 00:47:55.622
(sizzles)

626
00:47:58.625 --> 00:48:01.003
And we proceeded to have a lot of wine.

627
00:48:04.089 --> 00:48:06.550
MICHAEL: <i>At the end of the dinner. I said.</i>

628
00:48:06.633 --> 00:48:11.513
<i>"I think. it would be great to give Wolf.
two or three appearances on GMA."</i>

629
00:48:11.597 --> 00:48:15.267
The guy said. "Sounds like a good idea."

630
00:48:16.351 --> 00:48:18.437
<i>Because I'm an agent.
I pulled out a napkin.</i>

631
00:48:18.520 --> 00:48:22.608
<i>and I wrote this all out on the napkin.
dated it. and had him sign it.</i>

632
00:48:23.066 --> 00:48:24.943
And we had a contract.

633
00:48:28.363 --> 00:48:30.324
One of the most celebrated chefs
in Hollywood.

634
00:48:30.407 --> 00:48:31.783
is a young man named Wolfgang Puck.

635
00:48:31.867 --> 00:48:35.162
and he has cooked for all the rich
and the famous from all over the world.

636
00:48:35.245 --> 00:48:37.873
Today. he's going to cook for us
and it's nice to have you with us.

637
00:48:37.956 --> 00:48:39.541
-Thank you very much.
-Welcome. What are you cooking?

638
00:48:39.625 --> 00:48:41.627
We're going to make
a luxurious hamburger today.

639
00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:42.753
-All right.
-We have here...

640
00:48:42.836 --> 00:48:47.299
WOLFGANG: <i>Being live for the first time
on national television</i>

641
00:48:47.382 --> 00:48:48.926
<i>was such a big deal for me.</i>

642
00:48:49.009 --> 00:48:50.969
...different. we have here
a little bit of blue cheese.

643
00:48:51.053 --> 00:48:54.848
I was confident in my cooking.
but I was nervous looking at the cameras.

644
00:48:54.932 --> 00:48:58.644
which camera to look at.
I wanted it to be perfect.

645
00:48:58.727 --> 00:49:00.228
<i>So that way they ask me to come back.</i>

646
00:49:00.312 --> 00:49:02.940
Put it right in the middle
and close it up.

647
00:49:03.023 --> 00:49:05.484
MICHAEL:
<i>In those days. it was a very simple way</i>

648
00:49:05.567 --> 00:49:08.028
<i>of defining what was successful.</i>

649
00:49:08.111 --> 00:49:11.031
<i>by how many calls came
into the switchboard at the network.</i>

650
00:49:11.114 --> 00:49:13.075
WOLFGANG: We're gonna sauté them
really fast.

651
00:49:13.492 --> 00:49:17.537
After the first appearance.
we called everyone in our company.

652
00:49:17.621 --> 00:49:19.915
and had them call every relative they had.

653
00:49:19.998 --> 00:49:23.001
And the network lit up in L.A.
and New York.

654
00:49:23.085 --> 00:49:27.923
The switchboard lit up with people calling
saying who is that cute little guy?

655
00:49:28.006 --> 00:49:33.303
He's so fantastic. love those recipes.
all scripted by us and it worked.

656
00:49:33.387 --> 00:49:36.306
He just blew up like a movie star.

657
00:49:36.390 --> 00:49:38.100
-(audience applause)
-DAVID: Hi. how are you?

658
00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:42.020
Best-selling pizza
is the duck sausage pizza.

659
00:49:42.104 --> 00:49:43.647
JOAN: That's what I'm talking about.

660
00:49:43.730 --> 00:49:45.732
You want one too? Here.

661
00:49:45.816 --> 00:49:47.776
-(laughs)
-All right. good.

662
00:49:47.859 --> 00:49:50.529
LAURIE:
<i>Wolf started doing every morning show</i>

663
00:49:50.612 --> 00:49:51.863
<i>and late-night show.</i>

664
00:49:51.947 --> 00:49:54.449
All right. hi. The vegetables are here.
How are you?

665
00:49:54.533 --> 00:49:58.412
LAURIE: <i>He could be with David Letterman
and make jokes.</i>

666
00:49:58.954 --> 00:50:03.709
He just knew how to be himself.
and you just loved him.

667
00:50:03.792 --> 00:50:04.960
DAVID: Where do you get your recipes?

668
00:50:05.043 --> 00:50:07.838
You know. I'm cooking for 25 years already
so it's easy to make...

669
00:50:07.921 --> 00:50:09.798
You're probably younger
than I am. aren't you?

670
00:50:09.881 --> 00:50:11.174
Oh. much younger. yeah.

671
00:50:12.759 --> 00:50:15.971
JANNIS: <i>Every journalist
wanted to interview him constantly.</i>

672
00:50:16.054 --> 00:50:19.433
There were always photo shoots.
It was nuts.

673
00:50:19.808 --> 00:50:21.727
It's okay. We have enough for everybody.

674
00:50:23.729 --> 00:50:26.982
RUTH: <i>In the mid '80s.
I went with him to Cleveland.</i>

675
00:50:27.065 --> 00:50:29.401
And I go with Wolf to rent a car

676
00:50:29.484 --> 00:50:33.697
and the woman in the car rental
says to him.

677
00:50:33.780 --> 00:50:36.158
"My God. it's Wolfgang Puck.
you're that chef."

678
00:50:36.241 --> 00:50:39.870
And I thought. "Okay. the age
of the celebrity chef has begun."

679
00:50:39.995 --> 00:50:42.247
Hello. madam. how are you?
I'm Wolfgang Puck.

680
00:50:43.248 --> 00:50:44.708
No. you're not.

681
00:50:44.791 --> 00:50:47.544
PATRICK:

682
00:50:57.596 --> 00:51:00.015
(audience cheering)

683
00:51:01.183 --> 00:51:02.184
Let's grill.

684
00:51:02.642 --> 00:51:03.602
Good morning.

685
00:51:05.145 --> 00:51:07.230
JANNIS: <i>Wolfgang Puck
deserves so much respect.</i>

686
00:51:07.314 --> 00:51:11.860
<i>for how he transformed celebrity
for chefs...</i>

687
00:51:13.070 --> 00:51:15.405
<i>with TV shows. cook-offs.</i>

688
00:51:16.406 --> 00:51:18.325
<i>He set the stage for all of that.</i>

689
00:51:20.327 --> 00:51:22.954
PAT:
<i>The Tom Cruise of chefs is Wolfgang Puck.</i>

690
00:51:23.038 --> 00:51:25.957
<i>His own wedding was featured
on</i> The Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous.

691
00:51:26.041 --> 00:51:28.627
<i>This is a cook we're talking about.</i>

692
00:51:29.461 --> 00:51:33.048
PATRICK:

693
00:51:40.180 --> 00:51:43.308
Here we go with my old car here.
My limousine is ready.

694
00:51:44.976 --> 00:51:47.979
The place is Spago's.
the legendary "in" restaurant

695
00:51:48.063 --> 00:51:51.149
owned. operated by.
and featuring the cuisine

696
00:51:51.233 --> 00:51:54.111
of the equally legendary chef.
Wolfgang Puck.

697
00:51:54.194 --> 00:51:55.904
Puck's is a household name.

698
00:51:55.987 --> 00:51:59.658
He is arguably the best-known.
most successful chef of our time.

699
00:51:59.741 --> 00:52:03.745
My dream really was to have one
little restaurant. maybe write a cookbook.

700
00:52:03.829 --> 00:52:06.373
And you've made more money at it
than you ever dreamed you would.

701
00:52:06.456 --> 00:52:10.085
Yeah. absolutely. And I live better
than I ever thought I would live.

702
00:52:10.168 --> 00:52:13.755
But you know. the money aspect
is not what really drives me.

703
00:52:16.049 --> 00:52:20.470
RUTH: <i>Despite the fact
that he was enormously successful.</i>

704
00:52:20.929 --> 00:52:22.556
<i>enormously respected.</i>

705
00:52:23.723 --> 00:52:29.396
Wolf was still sort of stunned
by his success.

706
00:52:30.605 --> 00:52:35.443
When you caught him off guard.
you would find that he was afraid.

707
00:52:36.945 --> 00:52:39.531
<i>That he'd be back in the basement
peeling potatoes.</i>

708
00:52:39.614 --> 00:52:43.952
that. at any moment. you know. the coach
was gonna turn back into a pumpkin.

709
00:52:44.494 --> 00:52:46.788
So. he was not slowing down.

710
00:52:48.123 --> 00:52:50.542
All right. now we're gonna start. huh?

711
00:52:50.625 --> 00:52:52.127
BARBARA: <i>I think. all those shows.</i>

712
00:52:52.252 --> 00:52:56.006
<i>and all the press that started
to be generated led to an explosion.</i>

713
00:52:56.339 --> 00:52:58.717
It was frenetic.

714
00:52:59.217 --> 00:53:04.472
EMCEE: <i>Your restaurateur of this year
is Wolfgang Puck.</i>

715
00:53:04.556 --> 00:53:07.350
Every city he went to.
somebody was like. "Come open here.

716
00:53:07.434 --> 00:53:11.313
Come into business with us."
Everybody wanted a piece of Wolf.

717
00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:18.028
WOLFGANG: <i>Johnny Carson
used to come often to Spago.</i>

718
00:53:18.361 --> 00:53:20.947
One day. he said.
"Can I take some pizzas to go?"

719
00:53:21.031 --> 00:53:24.117
So. he took like a pile.
like 10. 12 pizzas to go.

720
00:53:24.784 --> 00:53:26.494
<i>And by the second or third time. I said.</i>

721
00:53:26.578 --> 00:53:28.496
<i>"Johnny.
what are you doing with my pizzas?"</i>

722
00:53:28.580 --> 00:53:32.918
He says. "I put them in the freezer.
I just loved it." What the heck?

723
00:53:33.960 --> 00:53:38.506
<i>So out of that.
really started my frozen pizza business.</i>

724
00:53:42.010 --> 00:53:45.555
RUTH: <i>Wolfgang was the first chef
since Chef Boyardee.</i>

725
00:53:45.639 --> 00:53:48.475
to say. "What if I take my food.

726
00:53:48.850 --> 00:53:52.646
and make it available to people
who are home cooks?"

727
00:53:53.939 --> 00:53:56.816
After that. he became a brand.

728
00:53:56.900 --> 00:53:58.401
REPORTER 3:
<i>World-renowned chef Wolfgang Puck.</i>

729
00:53:58.485 --> 00:53:59.486
REPORTER 4: Wolfgang Puck.

730
00:53:59.569 --> 00:54:01.279
<i>Celebrity chef Wolfgang Puck.</i>

731
00:54:02.239 --> 00:54:03.531
LAURIE: <i>Every month.</i>

732
00:54:03.615 --> 00:54:07.285
<i>there seemed to be a new restaurant
opening throughout California.</i>

733
00:54:07.661 --> 00:54:09.329
<i>And then around the world.</i>

734
00:54:10.288 --> 00:54:12.958
It was like how is he everywhere?

735
00:54:13.291 --> 00:54:15.335
Beautiful set we get to talk about.

736
00:54:15.418 --> 00:54:17.671
BARBARA: <i>We opened Spago Las Vegas.</i>

737
00:54:17.963 --> 00:54:20.006
<i>and then we started building cafés.</i>

738
00:54:20.966 --> 00:54:24.261
Things just kept blossoming
and blossoming and blossoming.

739
00:54:24.552 --> 00:54:28.723
Now. that's what I call fusion.
I could sell them on the Internet.

740
00:54:28.807 --> 00:54:29.766
(smooches)

741
00:54:30.267 --> 00:54:32.852
WOLFGANG: <i>Everything was running
at a hundred miles an hour.</i>

742
00:54:33.019 --> 00:54:37.691
Everything was a huge success.
beyond my greatest dreams.

743
00:54:39.192 --> 00:54:43.405
<i>But I still always felt
that something is missing.</i>

744
00:54:47.409 --> 00:54:50.161
So good to have you here in Atlanta.
no less.

745
00:54:50.245 --> 00:54:52.664
In Atlanta. You are so busy.
You got the frozen pizza line.

746
00:54:52.747 --> 00:54:54.708
You got 63 restaurants.
you got all this stuff.

747
00:54:54.791 --> 00:54:56.209
you got a new four-month-old baby.

748
00:54:56.626 --> 00:54:59.296
I think. it keeps me busy.
keeps me out of trouble that way.

749
00:54:59.379 --> 00:55:00.755
I guess so.

750
00:55:00.839 --> 00:55:03.383
When I thought about becoming a father.

751
00:55:03.466 --> 00:55:08.430
and how I gonna treat my children
especially. I was so nervous.

752
00:55:08.513 --> 00:55:12.100
The last thing I wanted to be
is like my stepfather.

753
00:55:13.435 --> 00:55:17.355
WOLFGANG: <i>But Barbara had always wanted
to start a family.</i>

754
00:55:18.023 --> 00:55:22.569
<i>So. when our first child came.
I was already 40 years old.</i>

755
00:55:23.153 --> 00:55:25.864
<i>A few years later I had a second child.</i>

756
00:55:26.740 --> 00:55:30.201
But I also was expanding
like crazy at that time.

757
00:55:31.286 --> 00:55:35.206
BARBARA: <i>I think. because we were building
a business and he was always so nervous.</i>

758
00:55:35.290 --> 00:55:36.958
<i>about things not going right.</i>

759
00:55:37.042 --> 00:55:43.131
primarily. the caretaking of the children
fell to me mostly.

760
00:55:43.965 --> 00:55:46.051
<i>He was always at the restaurants.</i>

761
00:55:47.635 --> 00:55:50.138
WOLFGANG: <i>Certain nights. I say.
"Listen. I shouldn't be in the restaurant.</i>

762
00:55:50.221 --> 00:55:51.723
<i>I should be at home with my son."</i>

763
00:55:51.806 --> 00:55:54.517
But. you know.
I think. we try to juggle both of them.

764
00:55:54.601 --> 00:55:57.395
to spend time with him
and to also spend time at the restaurant.

765
00:55:57.479 --> 00:56:00.190
because we feel like the restaurants
are also our children.

766
00:56:00.273 --> 00:56:02.275
(somber music)

767
00:56:02.359 --> 00:56:04.736
MICHAEL:
<i>I felt that he was spread way too thin.</i>

768
00:56:05.487 --> 00:56:07.947
<i>I tried to get him to focus
on fewer things.</i>

769
00:56:08.031 --> 00:56:10.825
but he did what he wanted to do.

770
00:56:11.534 --> 00:56:12.952
<i>He tried to do everything.</i>

771
00:56:13.870 --> 00:56:15.955
INTERVIEWER:
<i>How much time do you spend in the kitchen?</i>

772
00:56:16.247 --> 00:56:18.249
Are there days
when you don't cook anything yourself?

773
00:56:18.333 --> 00:56:21.669
You know. there are days when I have
to talk with accountants

774
00:56:21.753 --> 00:56:23.880
-and with lawyers and...
-Reporters.

775
00:56:23.963 --> 00:56:26.883
Yeah. no.
and that's my worst day probably.

776
00:56:29.177 --> 00:56:32.472
BYRON: <i>When I was growing up.
my dad was always working.</i>

777
00:56:35.308 --> 00:56:38.686
<i>I remember being in elementary school
and going to Spago.</i>

778
00:56:38.770 --> 00:56:42.357
four nights out of the week for dinner.
just so I could have a family dinner.

779
00:56:43.733 --> 00:56:45.652
<i>It was hard to see him.</i>

780
00:56:49.989 --> 00:56:51.699
BARBARA: <i>I could not get his attention</i>

781
00:56:51.783 --> 00:56:53.952
<i>because he was busy doing this
and busy doing that.</i>

782
00:56:54.035 --> 00:56:58.206
I said. "If you want a relationship
and you want to really know your kids.

783
00:56:58.289 --> 00:57:00.250
you're gonna have to be there some time."

784
00:57:00.333 --> 00:57:03.420
I have a new thing in the office
over there for you.

785
00:57:03.503 --> 00:57:04.629
What is that?

786
00:57:06.172 --> 00:57:09.008
Well. your idea of a <i>plaisanterie</i>
and my idea of a <i>plaisanterie</i>

787
00:57:09.092 --> 00:57:10.468
are two different things so...

788
00:57:15.515 --> 00:57:17.183
NANCY: <i>Working with Wolf and Barbara.</i>

789
00:57:17.475 --> 00:57:21.729
I don't know if I've ever had worked
with such a team before.

790
00:57:23.982 --> 00:57:27.610
<i>Together. the two of them made something</i>

791
00:57:27.694 --> 00:57:31.990
that I don't think anybody else
had done before.

792
00:57:35.076 --> 00:57:36.953
<i>But at that time.</i>

793
00:57:37.036 --> 00:57:41.791
<i>journalists were so captivated by Wolfgang</i>

794
00:57:41.875 --> 00:57:44.711
<i>and his winning personality</i>

795
00:57:45.420 --> 00:57:48.173
<i>that what was hard for Barbara.</i>

796
00:57:48.256 --> 00:57:51.968
is that she worked every bit as hard
as Wolfgang

797
00:57:52.051 --> 00:57:54.429
and she didn't get the attention.

798
00:57:54.512 --> 00:57:58.516
And I think that wore her down.

799
00:58:00.143 --> 00:58:02.395
(somber music)

800
00:58:04.397 --> 00:58:08.776
BYRON: <i>As a kid. I didn't understand
like what divorce was.</i>

801
00:58:10.028 --> 00:58:14.032
I didn't understand that my dad
wasn't going to be in the house anymore.

802
00:58:16.784 --> 00:58:19.913
<i>Until I went to school
on the first day of second grade.</i>

803
00:58:19.996 --> 00:58:23.583
and my mom walked me into school
and she turned me around.

804
00:58:23.666 --> 00:58:25.877
and she was like very serious
with me for a second.

805
00:58:25.960 --> 00:58:29.672
She was just like. "If anyone says
anything about your parents

806
00:58:29.756 --> 00:58:33.134
or what's going on at home.
don't say anything to them.

807
00:58:33.218 --> 00:58:35.720
You don't need to.
Don't get angry with them.

808
00:58:35.803 --> 00:58:38.431
Just leave it alone.
and you can talk to me about it."

809
00:58:42.018 --> 00:58:46.147
WOLFGANG:
<i>When we got divorced. it was really hard.</i>

810
00:58:48.983 --> 00:58:52.487
<i>Barbara was always very supportive of me.</i>

811
00:58:54.906 --> 00:58:57.951
<i>She always believed in me.</i>

812
00:59:02.997 --> 00:59:08.503
<i>Often I would sit at Spago.
looking out the window...</i>

813
00:59:09.546 --> 00:59:12.924
<i>and ask myself. who am I?</i>

814
00:59:18.054 --> 00:59:19.180
<i>Am I a chef?</i>

815
00:59:21.933 --> 00:59:23.309
<i>Am I a restaurant?</i>

816
00:59:25.603 --> 00:59:27.313
<i>Am I a character?</i>

817
00:59:29.357 --> 00:59:32.527
<i>Am I a guy who has never enough?</i>

818
00:59:40.034 --> 00:59:42.036
(dramatic music)

819
00:59:57.510 --> 00:59:59.512
(speaking German)

820
01:00:03.808 --> 01:00:05.810
(laughs)

821
01:00:43.640 --> 01:00:44.932
(sniffs)

822
01:00:46.893 --> 01:00:48.978
(dramatic music)

823
01:00:52.315 --> 01:00:54.734
(Christina in German)

824
01:01:29.811 --> 01:01:31.896
(in English)
WOLFGANG: <i>My whole life</i>

825
01:01:31.979 --> 01:01:33.898
<i>I had this fear of failure.</i>

826
01:01:35.692 --> 01:01:38.611
I had this fear of going backwards.

827
01:01:41.864 --> 01:01:47.412
I always had this desire to be successful.

828
01:01:48.037 --> 01:01:50.415
do more and do better.

829
01:01:52.375 --> 01:01:54.085
<i>But at the end of the day.</i>

830
01:01:54.961 --> 01:01:59.507
I didn't really know who I was
or what it was for.

831
01:02:01.217 --> 01:02:03.428
(dramatic music)

832
01:02:17.233 --> 01:02:21.112
BARBARA: <i>Our childhood memories
are visceral memories.</i>

833
01:02:23.197 --> 01:02:28.494
<i>Those memories of Austria
are part of his DNA.</i>

834
01:02:32.373 --> 01:02:34.375
<i>Not all of them are good memories.</i>

835
01:02:36.919 --> 01:02:41.174
<i>But part of me always felt
that maybe by doing this.</i>

836
01:02:41.257 --> 01:02:44.886
by cooking.
maybe you're rewriting your story.

837
01:02:48.931 --> 01:02:54.479
Wolfgang didn't start out because he knew
one day he would have a food company.

838
01:02:54.562 --> 01:02:58.316
and a TV show.
and restaurants around the world.

839
01:03:00.777 --> 01:03:03.279
NANCY: <i>He started out
because he loved to cook.</i>

840
01:03:04.071 --> 01:03:06.449
<i>and this was his life and his passion.</i>

841
01:03:14.957 --> 01:03:17.168
(Christina in German)

842
01:03:35.144 --> 01:03:38.356
(in English)
WOLFGANG: <i>I spent my whole life</i>

843
01:03:38.439 --> 01:03:39.982
<i>hating my stepfather.</i>

844
01:03:40.650 --> 01:03:42.527
<i>and trying to prove him wrong.</i>

845
01:03:44.737 --> 01:03:49.033
But looking back. sometimes. I think.

846
01:03:49.116 --> 01:03:52.203
maybe that whole thing made me stronger.

847
01:03:55.289 --> 01:03:58.584
<i>I realized all this time.</i>

848
01:03:59.001 --> 01:04:01.587
<i>I wasn't running away from anything.</i>

849
01:04:04.215 --> 01:04:08.010
<i>I was going after the thing I love to do.</i>

850
01:04:24.819 --> 01:04:26.821
(fire crackles)

851
01:04:39.876 --> 01:04:43.796
WOLFGANG: <i>We all make mistakes
when we go through life.</i>

852
01:04:46.007 --> 01:04:49.260
<i>Looking back and say.
"I should have. I could have".</i>

853
01:04:49.385 --> 01:04:51.053
<i>that's not gonna get me anywhere.</i>

854
01:04:54.015 --> 01:04:59.145
I just think if you spend the time
talking about the past.

855
01:04:59.687 --> 01:05:01.522
you forget to talk about the future.

856
01:05:01.606 --> 01:05:04.775
what are the possibilities.
what can we do next?

857
01:05:07.862 --> 01:05:13.034
<i>So. when I moved Spago
from West Hollywood to Beverly Hills.</i>

858
01:05:13.326 --> 01:05:16.704
<i>I said. "What are we gonna do different?
I have to do something different."</i>

859
01:05:18.247 --> 01:05:21.334
<i>When I was at Ma Maison.
we made modern French food.</i>

860
01:05:21.834 --> 01:05:25.796
<i>I opened Spago.
was like a mixture of California.</i>

861
01:05:26.130 --> 01:05:28.132
<i>Then Chinois was Asian.</i>

862
01:05:29.550 --> 01:05:34.513
<i>But Austria.
it's where I fell in love with cooking.</i>

863
01:05:35.139 --> 01:05:39.226
And yet.
I never cooked Austrian food actually.

864
01:05:39.310 --> 01:05:43.022
I said. "You know what? I'm gonna
put something Austrian on the menu."

865
01:05:44.065 --> 01:05:46.067
(lively music)

866
01:05:52.657 --> 01:05:54.200
WOLFGANG: <i>For me as a child.</i>

867
01:05:54.283 --> 01:05:57.119
<i>I remember the wiener schnitzel
my mother used to make.</i>

868
01:05:58.454 --> 01:06:02.041
<i>I remember she made a soup
with liver dumplings that I used to love</i>

869
01:06:03.084 --> 01:06:06.671
<i>or the palatschinken. or kaiserschmarrn.</i>

870
01:06:08.756 --> 01:06:13.844
These were things I remember
the most about our family.

871
01:06:13.928 --> 01:06:15.930
the positive part of our family.

872
01:06:19.225 --> 01:06:23.104
RUTH: <i>You know. we all have the taste
of our childhood in our heads.</i>

873
01:06:23.980 --> 01:06:27.858
<i>And when he made the menu
at Spago Beverly Hills.</i>

874
01:06:27.942 --> 01:06:31.028
<i>it's like I'm gonna put my dish on there.</i>

875
01:06:31.112 --> 01:06:35.282
and I don't care if it even goes
with the rest of the Spago menu.

876
01:06:35.366 --> 01:06:36.617
I'm gonna put it on there.

877
01:06:39.161 --> 01:06:44.208
And of course. we all order it
all the time because it's fantastic.

878
01:06:45.292 --> 01:06:47.503
(lively music)

879
01:07:03.394 --> 01:07:05.688
Wolfgang does so many things.

880
01:07:06.147 --> 01:07:09.233
NANCY: <i>But I always knew that
he was never more comfortable</i>

881
01:07:09.316 --> 01:07:12.987
<i>than in his chef jacket.
in front of a stove.</i>

882
01:07:13.696 --> 01:07:16.574
That's when Wolfgang feels like Wolfgang.

883
01:07:20.077 --> 01:07:25.082
I think Wolfgang's greatest impact
is the joy that he brings to cooking.

884
01:07:31.547 --> 01:07:33.883
MICHAEL: <i>There's a warmth wherever he is.</i>

885
01:07:33.966 --> 01:07:37.762
He just generates it.
He walks into a room and it lights up.

886
01:07:40.723 --> 01:07:45.978
People say food is medicine.
For Wolf. food is the conduit of love.

887
01:07:51.025 --> 01:07:55.154
WOLFGANG: <i>To my big surprise.
wiener schnitzel was a huge success.</i>

888
01:07:55.237 --> 01:07:56.238
Everybody loved it.

889
01:07:59.241 --> 01:08:04.371
<i>In a way. it reminded me.
that for me. food is family.</i>

890
01:08:05.581 --> 01:08:09.835
Making people feel happy
is my purpose in life.

891
01:08:29.105 --> 01:08:32.274
WOLFGANG: I think. it's interesting.
you know. how we live our life.

892
01:08:32.858 --> 01:08:36.028
We forget how short
it is actually. you know?

893
01:08:39.281 --> 01:08:44.745
So. I think. now I'm a little bit
more stingy with my time.

894
01:08:50.543 --> 01:08:52.002
CREW:

895
01:08:53.045 --> 01:08:56.048
Oh. because I only have
that many summers left. really.

896
01:09:11.564 --> 01:09:12.940
How we do. all right?

897
01:09:13.023 --> 01:09:16.861
-CHEF 3: Great. chef. Yes. chef.
-What we having. bread?

898
01:09:16.944 --> 01:09:19.405
-CHEF 4: Bread. brioche.
-Brioche.

899
01:09:20.072 --> 01:09:21.699
-CHEF 5: Hi. chef!
-What are we making?

900
01:09:21.782 --> 01:09:23.784
We're making chocolate.
jumbo chocolate chip cookies.

901
01:09:23.868 --> 01:09:26.495
-But make them really dark. huh?
-Yes. chef.

902
01:09:26.579 --> 01:09:29.832
-No white. no more white cookies.
-No white cookies.

903
01:09:29.915 --> 01:09:30.958
Yeah.

904
01:09:31.041 --> 01:09:33.502
WOLFGANG: <i>When people ask me
what I'm the most proud of.</i>

905
01:09:33.586 --> 01:09:35.671
it's really longevity.

906
01:09:37.006 --> 01:09:38.757
How's the tuna? Get me a little of that.

907
01:09:40.509 --> 01:09:43.304
WOLFGANG:
<i>Staying in business for so many years.</i>

908
01:09:43.387 --> 01:09:45.931
<i>it really takes a lot of hard work.</i>

909
01:09:46.015 --> 01:09:47.850
-Don't go when cooking. okay?
-Yes. chef.

910
01:09:48.726 --> 01:09:52.104
WOLFGANG: <i>I think. we always
have to continue to change.</i>

911
01:09:54.231 --> 01:09:59.361
And I really believe we get new ideas
often from the younger ones.

912
01:10:00.696 --> 01:10:01.864
(Wolfgang mumbles)

913
01:10:03.824 --> 01:10:07.203
WOLFGANG: <i>Now. I have the pleasure
and the luxury</i>

914
01:10:07.286 --> 01:10:09.538
<i>to have so many talented young chefs.</i>

915
01:10:09.622 --> 01:10:11.874
like my son. Byron.

916
01:10:13.167 --> 01:10:15.419
-What. are you gonna put the egg in there?
-Yeah.

917
01:10:15.502 --> 01:10:17.087
-Let's do that.
-Okay here. I'll help you.

918
01:10:17.171 --> 01:10:18.047
Thank you.

919
01:10:19.173 --> 01:10:22.301
-Hopefully. I don't put the shells in.
-Nailed it.

920
01:10:23.844 --> 01:10:27.890
BYRON: <i>I stared working at Spago
as a 13-year-old. peeling potatoes.</i>

921
01:10:28.599 --> 01:10:34.355
And seeing him there as the kind of leader
was just amazing for me to watch as a kid.

922
01:10:38.984 --> 01:10:41.195
<i>Everything he did. I wanted to do it.</i>

923
01:10:42.488 --> 01:10:44.865
I felt very comfortable
in this environment.

924
01:10:44.949 --> 01:10:47.076
and it felt like something I could really.

925
01:10:47.159 --> 01:10:50.663
really put my heart into.
and spend the rest of my life doing.

926
01:10:50.746 --> 01:10:52.748
(sizzles)

927
01:10:55.501 --> 01:10:57.628
-A little more.
-Okay. yeah. make it nice and crispy.

928
01:10:57.711 --> 01:10:58.712
Yeah.

929
01:11:00.547 --> 01:11:03.592
BYRON: <i>Now. I get to be passionate
not only about the same thing.</i>

930
01:11:04.093 --> 01:11:08.138
but I get to have one of the best teachers
in the world helping me along the way.

931
01:11:08.973 --> 01:11:11.392
That remind me that sound
that my mother used to make.

932
01:11:11.475 --> 01:11:12.559
Yeah.
(chuckles)

933
01:11:14.019 --> 01:11:18.440
RUTH: <i>The fact that Byron really wants
to be in the business.</i>

934
01:11:18.524 --> 01:11:21.944
I don't think there could be
greater joy for Wolf than that.

935
01:11:22.027 --> 01:11:26.282
I mean. to have a son
who wants to follow in his footsteps.

936
01:11:26.365 --> 01:11:27.616
I think. it's huge for him.

937
01:11:28.200 --> 01:11:30.828
-Folks. we enjoying ourselves over here?
-CUSTOMER: We are.

938
01:11:30.911 --> 01:11:31.954
Doing well?

939
01:11:35.374 --> 01:11:41.213
As a younger chef. I think.
I was so absorbed in my profession.

940
01:11:41.547 --> 01:11:48.429
of becoming successful
that I neglected my duty as a father.

941
01:11:50.681 --> 01:11:55.519
WOLFGANG: <i>But now. it's a great thing
to work with my son in the business.</i>

942
01:11:56.353 --> 01:12:00.941
And I think for a father. there's nothing
better than seeing your kids successful.

943
01:12:06.196 --> 01:12:10.367
-GELILA: No. seriously.
-Put down the cutting board right there.

944
01:12:11.118 --> 01:12:14.455
Who wants to be sous-chef.
because I hate cutting onions. seriously.

945
01:12:14.538 --> 01:12:15.664
Okay. I do.

946
01:12:15.748 --> 01:12:19.001
-That is the best use of Wolfgang Puck.
-Okay.

947
01:12:19.084 --> 01:12:21.628
-Exactly. Cut two onions.
-Okay.

948
01:12:21.712 --> 01:12:23.505
Look at that.
I'm the chopper of the onions.

949
01:12:23.589 --> 01:12:25.507
ALEXANDER:
I actually think I should be the one.

950
01:12:25.591 --> 01:12:29.094
Okay. you're going to start it
with the tip on the board like that.

951
01:12:29.178 --> 01:12:31.263
And push through so it
makes it really easy.

952
01:12:31.347 --> 01:12:32.973
-OLIVER: <i>Si. señor.</i>
-Yeah.

953
01:12:33.057 --> 01:12:34.391
-(laughing)
-BYRON: Here. use this.

954
01:12:34.475 --> 01:12:35.768
But it kinda tastes good. though.

955
01:12:35.851 --> 01:12:37.978
WOLFGANG: <i>When I look back today</i>

956
01:12:38.062 --> 01:12:41.106
<i>and ask what could I have done different?</i>

957
01:12:41.398 --> 01:12:44.651
<i>For sure it was spend
more time with the family.</i>

958
01:12:44.735 --> 01:12:46.945
I really missed my kids growing up.

959
01:12:47.029 --> 01:12:48.655
BYRON:
Uh. well. you have to go on Sundays.

960
01:12:48.739 --> 01:12:50.199
-Thankfully. I've never...
-(Alexander groans)

961
01:12:50.282 --> 01:12:52.159
-It is good.
-GELILA: I still need a lot.

962
01:12:52.242 --> 01:12:54.787
-That's fine. That's fine.
-No. don't take my cheese. Hey.

963
01:12:54.870 --> 01:12:59.208
WOLFGANG: <i>But I'm now married to Gelila.
and we have two young boys.</i>

964
01:12:59.750 --> 01:13:02.753
So. now. I know how precious time is.

965
01:13:03.504 --> 01:13:05.506
-No kisses.
-(laughs)

966
01:13:08.008 --> 01:13:09.676
BYRON: Y'all ready to eat?

967
01:13:09.760 --> 01:13:12.221
(both laugh)

968
01:13:12.304 --> 01:13:14.098
-GELILA: Here's to my boys.
-Cheers.

969
01:13:14.181 --> 01:13:15.974
All right. good job. Byron.

970
01:13:16.058 --> 01:13:18.560
-Cheers. sir.
-Cheers.

971
01:13:19.520 --> 01:13:23.273
GELILA: <i>At the end of the day.
you have to live by an example.</i>

972
01:13:24.441 --> 01:13:28.278
Wolf's experience pushed him towards love.

973
01:13:29.363 --> 01:13:34.993
<i>to reconnect as a family
and become the person he wants to become.</i>

974
01:13:37.996 --> 01:13:42.209
That he's able to influence
not only his children.

975
01:13:42.292 --> 01:13:47.840
but also anyone who is able
to overcome challenges.

976
01:13:49.425 --> 01:13:51.385
<i>I think. that's a beautiful story.</i>

977
01:13:54.847 --> 01:13:57.057
(light music)

978
01:14:02.062 --> 01:14:06.525
BYRON: <i>I don't think there's better
examples of truly coming from nothing.</i>

979
01:14:06.608 --> 01:14:11.113
and building something incredible
than Wolfgang Puck.

980
01:14:16.827 --> 01:14:22.249
I think. the real moral of Wolf's story
is believe in yourself.

981
01:14:22.791 --> 01:14:28.589
Know what you're good at.
take chances and you can be a success.

982
01:14:34.470 --> 01:14:38.098
RUTH: <i>Today.
there are hundreds of thousands.</i>

983
01:14:38.182 --> 01:14:40.642
<i>if not millions of people
who work in kitchens.</i>

984
01:14:40.726 --> 01:14:46.064
who aspire to be Wolfgang Puck
and who will take heart from his story.

985
01:14:46.148 --> 01:14:48.775
(all cheer)

986
01:14:48.859 --> 01:14:53.113
The most important lesson I learned
from Wolfgang is not to be afraid.

987
01:14:54.531 --> 01:15:01.205
His dedication. willingness to sacrifice
is what made him what he is.

988
01:15:02.998 --> 01:15:05.667
-We've gotta lean forward. it's very hot.
-The knife is...

989
01:15:05.751 --> 01:15:07.419
(laughs)

990
01:15:08.212 --> 01:15:09.213
Hot.

991
01:15:11.965 --> 01:15:16.136
BARBARA: <i>I think. Wolf's legacy
is in and of itself love.</i>

992
01:15:17.513 --> 01:15:20.641
<i>If you lead with your heart and your mind.</i>

993
01:15:20.724 --> 01:15:23.519
<i>and if you love what you do...</i>

994
01:15:24.895 --> 01:15:26.688
that's a life well lived.

995
01:15:34.112 --> 01:15:37.783
WOLFGANG: <i>I really believe
we have to have purpose in life.</i>

996
01:15:40.452 --> 01:15:45.457
<i>Nothing comes easy.
but if you believe in something.</i>

997
01:15:45.541 --> 01:15:47.918
<i>you have to follow your dreams.</i>

998
01:15:54.258 --> 01:15:59.304
<i>I hope I will end up doing the thing
I love to do</i>

999
01:16:00.931 --> 01:16:03.100
<i>until I take my last breath.</i>

1000
01:16:10.941 --> 01:16:13.151
(closing theme music)



